reviewText: let me start off by saying if you are a wwe fan, you have probably seen this on tv,but for people like me who dont have cable anymore, this is great, its 9hrs+ ofgreat smackdown action from 09-10, some great matches in here, and its on blu-rayso you cant go wrong, the picture quality is amazing, way better than the hd broadcasteverything is so crisp and clear, the sound is amazing too, it comes in 2 blu-raydisc, and the price is not bad either, considering youre getting a lot of wwe action,if you are a big wwe fan, i highly recommend this

reviewText: Following in the tradition of the 2009 RAW season set along with the upcoming ones for last years RAW (2010) & beginnings of both WWE RAW & WCW Nitro, WWE released a set showcasing the 2009-2010 season of SmackDown.  Now unlike how the "Best Of RAW" showcased the entire calender year, this only showcases the year long period from October 2009 to September 2010 which just also happened to be SmackDown's 10th season with then-SmackDown host Todd Grisham & Matt Striker hosting the DVD.  Now you already have a list of the various moments on this set so I won't repeat that but here's a review of the actual matches on the set.John Cena, D-Generation X, Undertaker vs. Randy Orton, Legacy, C.M. Punk - This was the main event on the season premiere of SmackDown with all participants in the 3 upcoming Hell In A Cell matches at that same PPV meeting here.  This was overall a very fun match to watch with everyone getting their various moments & momentum switching between both teams.  However as a tease for what's to come in the future, pay attention to the tension between Undertaker & Shawn Michaels based off the fact that this was the first time they were close to each other since WrestleMania 25.Oct. 2World Champion Undertaker vs. C.M. Punk - Punk got his rematch here after Undertaker won the World Championship at the Hell In A Cell PPV with the conditions being heavily in his favor.  The setup for this match was exactly like how they were at the Breaking Point PPV where Punk scored his "win" over Taker in that this was a submission match & Scott Armstrong was the referee while Teddy Long sat at ringside.  In order to avoid what happened last time, Taker was very cautious about his surroundings & at one point quickly escaped Punk's Anaconda Vice submission before he could get it fully applied & kept overpowering Punk to the point where he was just beating on him on the announce table.  At one point, Punk instructed Long to give him a chair only for the conspiracy that happened at Breaking Point to completely backfire on everyone leading Taker to avenge the loss & get some payback on those involved.Oct. 232 Out Of 3 Falls Match: Intercontinental Champion John Morrison vs. Dolph Ziggler - With Dolph chasing after the Intercontinental Title all summer against Mysterio & Morrison, this was his final opportunity at the title.  Both men were very athletic here with Grisham making the comment towards Morrison saying "he like Tony Hawk without the skateboard" as Morrison did some high risk moves that eventually did end up hurting himself when he landed on the floor.  Dolph was able to keep countering Starship Pain while targeting his ribs including doing a baseball slide into Morrison wrapped around the post.  This was a great match that told a good story with both men working hard (as usual).Nov. 20Mickie James vs. Beth Phoenix vs. Natalya - LayCool were at ringside (wearing Piggy James shirts) for this match to see who would get the title shot at the upcoming T.L.C. PPV.  This was a nice match but more memorable for this being the first confrontation between the two most powerful divas in WWE between Natayla & Beth as they kept throwing Mickie out of the ring a few times just so they could go at it leading to a few stalemates when going against each other, even knocking each other down with a double clothesline, and how an attempted Sharpshooter was turned in a Glam Slam.  Stay tuned after the match as what happened afterwords led to another diva returning to SmackDown.Dec. 4World Champion Undertaker vs. Rey Mysterio - This was a battle of "power vs. speed" as both men gained the momentum & used their strengths throughout this match.  Taker showcased his power by easily tossing Rey around early while being able to catch him during his attempts at high risk moves including swinging Rey into the railing at one point while Rey was able to keep avoiding Taker's moves like the apron legdrop & an attempted ram into the ringpost while also executing a suicide drive onto Taker on the outside.  Unfortunately Batista, who had an issue with both men, got involved here but it was the one man you least expected out of the three who left the lasting impression.Dec. 25Steel Cage Match: Rey Mysterio vs. Batista - With their previous #1 contenders match going to a no-contest due to the influence of Undertaker's presence, this was a steel cage to see who gets the title shot against Taker at the Royal Rumble PPV.  Rey knew he was in with a "caged animal" so he kept trying to escape the cage quickly whenever possible as Rey was also at a disadvantage because the stage prevented Rey from doing some of his offense like the 619.  Batista made it clear that his intention was to hurt Rey more than win the match as he just kept beating on him at various times & even once teased Rey as he was climbing the cage door only for Batista to ask to open the door just to give Rey false hope & stop him last minute.  Unfortunately Batista's actions would come back to haunt him in the end as Rey was able to get the best of Batista long enough to escape with a victory.Jan. 15John Morrison vs. R-Truth vs. Dolph Ziggler - This was a qualifying match for the WrestleMania Money In The Bank match with a side note of this match happened during the first season of NXT so future-Nexus member David Otunga is at ringside due to R-Truth being his then-pro.  With Dolph being the odd man out, you saw an early alliance against him in the beginning before it became every man for himself.  Morrison took some hard hits throughout this match such as an inverted bodyslam, his shoulder ramming into the ringpost, and being dropped on the back of his head.  Dolph got more aggressive as the match went on & took a nasty fall of his own with him falling off the top rope & head hitting the apron on the way down while Truth also banged his head off a sunset flip powerbomb by John Morrison.  In the end however, it's the man who got the pinfall (not the one who did the work) who walked out with the win.Feb. 26Edge vs. The Miz - This was their first ever meeting while Edge's second match back from his ankle injury while Miz was certainly on a role at this time in his career being both the United States Champion while recently winning the Tag Team Titles with Big Show.  This was a good match that got more competitive as it went on between both men that left me more impressed with The Miz.Feb. 26Undertaker vs. Drew McIntyre - After Drew McIntyre lost twice in Money In The Bank qualifying matches only to have them erased by Mr. McMahon to the disapproval of Teddy Long, Drew was put into this match against Undertaker.  This was a dominate squash by Undertaker with the bigger story being about who showed up & what happened after the match.Mar. 19Kane, Dolph Ziggler, Matt Hardy, Shelton Benjamin, Drew McIntyre vs. Christian, MVP, Jack Swagger, Evan Bourne, Kofi Kingston - On the final SmackDown before WrestleMania, this was a RAW vs. SmackDown 10 man tag featuring all the participants in the Money In The Bank match.  This was a fun tag match with everyone getting their time in the ring but the bigger story here was how everyone had issues with Drew McIntyre...including his own teammates.Mar. 26World Champion Jack Swagger vs. Edge vs. Chris Jericho - As seen in the segment before this match, Swagger cashed in his Money In The Bank contract to win the World Championship against Chris Jericho after Edge had already laid him out setting up this triple threat match.  This was Swagger's first title defense with Jericho's walking in with his ribs taped.  This was a great triple threat match as all three men worked well with each men  having opportunities to win the championship at one point while also doing other things like attempting to perform the other's signature moves & steal a win after the other person did the work.  Again, great triple threat match & the best performance Jack Swagger had as a World Champion.Apr. 16Handicap Match: Womens Champion Beth Phoenix vs. LayCool - While Beth Phoenix won the Womens Championship at Extreme Rules, she injured her knee a week before this match leading to Vickie Guerrero allowing McCool to cash in her rematch along with adding Layla making this a handicap match.  This match wasn't much past Beth showing her heavy strength even though she had a bad leg but it served it's purpose in having not only Beth drop the title but begin the story of LayCool being co-Womens Champions.  As a side note, pay attention after the match as I couldn't help but laugh at McCool & Vickie holding the title so high that "little" Layla couldn't reach it.May 14Rey Mysterio vs. C.M. Punk - Even though they were scheduled to meet days later at the Over The Limit PPV, they fought here in a match that was a step down from their previous PPV encounters but still a good match between the two.  However this was more about giving a preview of what the future was for Rey Mysterio if he didn't win his match at the PPV.May 14Battle Royal - The week before, Undertaker defeated Rey Mysterio to qualify for the World Title match at the Final 4 PPV only for Kane to reveal that he was attacked & beaten into a "vegetative" state causing this match to see who will get Taker's spot in the match.  This was your typical battle royal with a few moments such as the return of Finlay & Kane's dominate performance featuring confrontations with Luke Gallous & Rey Mysterio.June 4Matt Hardy vs. Drew McIntyre - For months Drew McIntyre was the "Chosen One" of Mr. McMahon allowing him to get away with almost anything he wanted on SmackDown while also causing people like Matt Hardy to get suspended but also injured & Kofi Kingston stripped of the Intercontinental Championship.  However with Mr. McMahon out due to the Nexus on RAW, Teddy reinstated Matt Hardy & put him in the match here against Drew.  Drew heavily worked over Matt's head with various moves like the Michonku driver from the top rope while also trying to stomp his head into the steel steps again.  Matt Hardy "refused to die" & got his vengeance against Drew before Teddy gave Drew more bad news afterwords.June 25Rey Mysterio & Big Show vs. Cody Rhodes & Jack Swagger - Big Show came out limping with his ankle hurt from the attack of Swagger & Rhodes earlier in the night.  This was a nice match telling a good story of Swagger & Rhodes keeping the "smaller" Mysterio in the ring & constantly trying to avoid Mysterio tagging in Show while Swagger also showcased just how lethal he could be with his anklelock submission.July 2Christian vs. Drew McIntyre - I'll admit I'm not the biggest fan of Drew McIntyre, I'll give credit where it's due here in that he put on a good match here with Christian based off in-ring storytelling alone as Christian hurt his shoulder early so Drew constantly worked on it throughout the match while Christian sold it non-stop.  A good match that had a well told story.July 30No Disqualification Match: Rey Mysterio vs. Jack Swagger - Mysterio came out limping with a bad ankle from the effects of Jack Swagger's anklelock.  With these two knowing each other so well, they were able to counter & avoid each other's signature moves early such as the anklelock & 619.  As expected in a match with these rules, it spilled into the crowd to outside in the street with a car almost hitting Swagger.  They ended up fighting out to the beach & water with Swagger eventually taking a swim...before Mysterio was tossed in himself by someone else who had a target on Rey.July 30Intercontinental Champion Kofi Kingston vs. Dolph Ziggler - Their previous two encounters saw Dolph walk away with the victory due to Vickie Guerrero's involvement so Kofi came out more aggressive than he's been in a long time & took more risk such as a suicide dive onto Dolph on the outside that saw him hit the announce table on the way down while Dolph focused on Kofi's shoulder after it was rammed into the post.  Vickie Guerrero once again played a part here leading to Dolph finally getting the Intercontinental Championship but stay tuned afterwords as what happened was perfectly summarized by the announcers, "KOFI WENT CRAZY!"Aug. 6, 2010Rey Mysterio vs. Alberto Del Rio - This was Alberto's debut match & worked over Rey's arm by ramming & stomping it into the ringside steps while also delivering a dropkick right to the arm at one point setting up Del Rio to score his first win using a cross arm breaker.  This was a great debut & showcasing for Alberto.Aug. 20Kaval vs. Drew McIntyre - This was the debut for the winner of the second season of NXT, Kaval.  This was pretty short but Kaval had a chance to showcase his superior speed & high risk moves while also taking some hard bumps like Drew backdropping him on the apron & hitting hit his head on the ringside barricade after he missed a high risk move.  Again, this was too short to be of anything really important but Kaval made the best of what he had even though we went down in defeat (which was the result of most of his matches hence why he left before the year was over.)Sept. 10Undertaker vs. C.M. Punk - Before the match, Punk sent the remaining members of the Straight Edge Society (Gallous & Mercury) to the back for him to fight Undertaker alone.  This was Taker's first match since returning from his attack during the memorial day weekend.  The story here was that Taker still hasn't recovered fully from that attack so he was more vulnerable than he usually is which was showcased various time such as him losing his balance doing the "old school" rope walk, Punk being able to kick out of his signature power moves that usually finish off his opposition like the chokeslam, and just being more exhausted & drained than normal as the match went on.  Both men told this story well & I actually enjoyed this match more than their series over the World Title a year earlier.Sept. 10There are no DVD extras however for those who purchase this on Blu-Ray will receive 3 additional matches featuring Chris Jericho & Big Show vs. Undertaker & Kane, Rey Mysterio vs. Shawn Michaels, and Matt Hardy vs. Alberto Del Rio along with some other bonus segments involving Kane & LayCool.  While there were some great quality matches that were left off here (DX vs. Hart Dynasty, 1st time Taker vs. Jericho match, Kofi vs. Christian), they were found on other DVD sets (Hart Family Anthology, Jericho, Highest Flyers) so I didn't mind that.  However there were still some matches & moments I would have loved to see replace others such as the HBK vs. Mysterio & Taker/Kane vs. Jericho/Show matches there were Blu-Ray extras be part of the original presentation along with the two NO DQ matches between Kane/Mysterio & Morrison/McIntyre.  Anyways I really liked this set (more than the RAW one) because SmackDown was always more of the "sports" brand of WWE's sports entertainment in regards to better quality wrestling matches along with the fact that they formatted this to have more heavy emphasis on SmackDown before WrestleMania as the show took a heavy hit in regards to talent leaving afterwords (Batista & Jericho & Edge & Morrison to RAW along with Taker & Punk out with injuries at various times).  So this is something I would check out as I enjoyed a high majority of SmackDown's 10th season.
